vectorData.altText: 4. A cartilaginous joint that does not permit movement is a _________________.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In a synostosis      , two bones fuse, as occurs with the normal maturation of the frontal or occipital bone, or the development of irregular bones such as the vertebrae or ossa coxae. 
In a fibrous synarthrosis     , two bones are joined by fibrous CT. Examples are the sutures joining the flat bones of the skull and the gomphoses that hold teeth in their bony sockets, which are both immoveable joints. In a syndesmosis, two bones are joined by a sheet of dense irregular CT; examples are the interosseous membranes between the radius and ulna, and between the tibia and fibula.
In a cartilaginous synarthrosis, two bones are jointed by cartilage. A synchondrosis       is immoveable; an example is the epiphyseal plate of a growing bone. A symphysis permits some movement; examples are the intervertebral discs and the pubic symphysis.
G. syn = together; ostosis = the formation or development of bone
G. syn = together; arthrosis = the formation or development of a joint
G. syn - together; chondrosis = the formation or development of cartilage
That's right! A synchondrosis is an immovable cartilaginous joint.
